      "sha256": "a3b4cdb9905ad841fa8f38eb60ba640da81244caf326d301d8e72ad13cd1b6e6",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "This may even hold with $k\\approx \\epsilon N^{1/2}$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "d103a06bc3ecd8278f29f6cd1f9aa95ac39a9e0f0a1679bec236344e41785265",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $F(N)$ be the size of the largest Sidon subset of $\\{1,\\ldots,N\\}$. Is it true that for every $k\\geq 1$ we have\\[F(N+k)\\leq F(N)+1\\]for all sufficiently large $N$?"
    }
